postmortem edit June 1: it appears results are being recalculated. As @Emil noted the result seemed inaccurate to me too. Still, i died on this one too, @Anneinak, and agree with your analysis. There's a down-side to using an error-squared approach to calculating results: the occasional question where the forecaster and/or the crowd/median get it wrong dominates the scoreboard. Being 10% or 30% off the mark when the crowd is 20% off makes next to no difference, but being 90% or 70% off when the crowd is 80% sure does! I haven't done the math but imagine that forecasting conservatively (closer to 50% than the true probability) would pay off greatly in the long run because it's the questions with the low-probability outcome - like this one - which dominate. I've not encountered error-squared evaluation before. Root-mean-square and mean-average-error are often used for evaluating forecasts for weather, e.g., tornados or solar power; perhaps they would give less punishing/lucky results for this game.

Edit: Post-mortem: Looks like the answer will be 'no'. Assuming that it is, I think I will have done better than I should have done if I had estimated base rate probabilities correctly. My statistical model uses base rates (in the form of historical daily movements) to build distributions for the eventual price level. However, this model assumes that volatility remains constant at its historical average. In reality, volatility varies. In particular, high volatility tends to follow high volatility. In other words, volatility is clustered. That is why economists use GARCH modeling which varies the volatility accordingly. In the case of the FTSE, the level dropped and stayed below the 4 April level, which led my model to assign a relatively high probability of 'no'. However, ideally my model would have used GARCH volatility to account for the fact that the FTSE could have easily bounced back up above the 4 April level.

On 24 May 2019, will the FTSE 100 close above the place it did on April 4? The crowd forecast has evened out to about 65% consistently and is more likely to be correct given the nearness of this forecast. The FTSE 100 has been and will be greatly impacted by Brexit - in early April the Brexit extension prompted a rise, so it’s likely that the more recent extension could do keep currency factors more stable. on April 4 the closing was 7,401.94, from there it’s been rising pretty steadily (except for the last few days.) Brexit isn’t the only factor, but the extension does support an increase from April barring unforeseen impacts. GDP growth is projected to increase slightly over the next year, but the U.S. China trade war could either positively or negatively impact all markets, depending on the outcome of a trade deal.

However, this direction will come late. Not impossible a General Election will be called at or about this date. This does not directly impact the markets but the election rhetoric might do, and could certainly unsettle announcements of major investment in FDI. Any further uncertainty or domestic problems - hate to say so, but Ireland, a hot summer in London, you name it - could affect confidence and a shift out of equities.

According to BOE data, the option-implied probability is a hair above 50%, so that's a good base rate. The FTSE 100 is a cap-weighted index of the largest cap companies that trade on the London Stock Exchange. This is important, because not all of the companies are neither domiciled or earn a majority of their income in the UK. This is important, because it means the index is "a weak indicator of the UK economy" (Wikipedia).
